dosbox9 — DOSBox 0.74-3 for 9front. Changelog.
(`pac9 changelog dosbox9` shows this; newest first.)

0.2.1 — 2026-07-17
  Rebuilt against a correctness pass on the cc9 C runtime (durable fsync, honest
  file locks, correct O_APPEND, per-thread errno, corrected float formatting).
  DOSBox itself is unchanged — same 0.74-3, same damage-rect GL9F presentation —
  and rendering was re-verified on bare metal (Commander Keen 1 boots to its
  title screen, pixel-correct). Substrate-only refresh.

0.2.0 — 2026-07-15
  Damage rects on by default: a blinking cursor costs ~1 KB, not 1 MB.

  0.1.0 presented every update as a FULL FRAME — a 1 MB pipe write plus a
  whole-window image reload, for a screen where 13 rows changed. It did that
  because the delta path was visibly wrong: on the Apogee "Galaxy" games
  (bmenace, keen4) old text stayed under new, and Halloween Harry showed a
  garbled band. Deltas are now correct and are the default.

  The bug was never the deltas. gl9win2's Image is ABGR32 — a format WITH an
  alpha channel — so Plan 9's draw(2) computes

      dst = src + dst*(1 - src.alpha)

  from the 4th byte of every pixel. Our frames declared no alpha, so that byte
  was 0, and every draw was an ADDITIVE BLEND instead of a replace: whatever was
  already on screen showed through, and colours crept brighter. Full frames
  looked correct only by accident — gl9win2 blacks the window before drawing
  one, and src + 0 == src. Sending opaque pixels fixes it; the window server is
  unchanged.

  Verified on bare metal (Shuttle DS57U, Broadwell): 12/12 games render, no
  regressions, and Harry's "garbled band" — long filed as a separate artifact —
  was the same bug and is gone.

  Set P9_FULLFRAMES=1 to force 0.1.0's whole-frame presentation.

  Also in this release:
    - Windows 3.11 for Workgroups runs, GUI and all — Program Manager, groups,
      mouse. No boot needed: WIN.COM is an ordinary DOS program, so point C: at
      an installed WINDOWS tree and run `win`.
    - Windows 98 boots to real mode via DOSBox's BOOT.COM (its own IO.SYS and
      COMMAND.COM, at an interactive A:\>). The Win98 GUI does NOT run and
      won't: VMM32.VXD needs protected-mode/V86 and IDE emulation that vanilla
      DOSBox 0.74 has never had. That's an upstream DOSBox limit, not a 9front
      one — Win98-in-DOSBox means DOSBox-X.
    - New README with the architecture, the build, and both Windows recipes.

  Unchanged: sound is wired but still unlistened-to; game startup is slow
  because the CPU core is the portable interpreter (dynrec needs W^X and a real
  mprotect, which cc9 hasn't got).

0.1.0
  First release. DOSBox 0.74-3 cross-compiled with cc9, presented to a rio
  window by gl9win2 (the alacritty9 window server, reused unmodified). All 118
  DOSBox .cpp compile unmodified; the port is really an SDL 1.2.15 port with a
  Plan 9 video/audio backend. 12 shareware/freeware DOS games verified rendering
  on bare metal. `dosbox9` boots to Z:\>, `dosbox9 <dir>` mounts it as C:.
  Games are not bundled — host/fetch-games.py pulls them from archive.org.
